cs -- t11 A Much-Desired Match: Playwriting, Stagecraft, and Entrepreneurship -- t12 The Peach Blossom Fan and Palace of Everlasting Life: History, Romance, and Performance -- tPart III Mid–Qing Dynasty: Zaju and Chuanqi Plays -- t13 Song of Dragon Well Tea and Other Court Plays: Stage Directions, Spectacle, and Panegyrics -- t14 The Eight-Court Pearl: Performance Scripts and Political Culture -- tPart IV Ming, Qing, and Modern Eras: Ritual Plays -- t15 Mulian Rescues His Mother: Play Structure, Ritual, and Soundscapes -- t16 The Story of Hua Guan Suo: Chantefable and Ritual Plays -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tVisual resources -- tGlossary-index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is a comprehensive and inviting introduction to the literary forms and cultural significance of Chinese drama as both text and performance. Each chapter offers an accessible overview and critical analysis of one or more plays—canonical as well as less frequently studied works—and their historical contexts. How to Read Chinese Drama highlights how each play sheds light on key aspects of the dramatic tradition, including genre conventions, staging practices, musical performance, audience participation, and political resonances, emphasizing interconnections among chapters. It brings together leading scholars spanning anthropology, art history, ethnomusicology, history, literature, and theater studies.How to Read Chinese Drama is straightforward, clear, and concise, written for undergraduate students and their instructors as well as a wider audience interested in world theater. For students of Chinese literature and language, the book provides questions to explore when reading, watching, and listening to plays, and it features bilingual excerpts. For teachers, an analytical table of contents, a theater-specific chronology of events, and lists of visual resources and translations provide pedagogical resources for exploring Chinese theater within broader cultural and comparative contexts. For theater practitioners, the volume offers deeply researched readings of important plays together with background on historical performance conventions, audience responses, and select modern adaptations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChinese dramaxHistory and criticism. 0aChinese dramaxTranslations into English. 7aDRAMA / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aLlamas, Regina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/sieb1864840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231546669423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231546669/original  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK